Determine Network Security Group Effective Rules

There's a reason why it's recommended that you usually enforce your NSGs at the subnet level, like a standard operating procedure on how you should manage the checkpoints in your building. It allows you to manage things easier because if you set NSGs at the nic level now you have to consider addtitonal things like:

For inbound traffic, Azure first processes network security group security rules for any associated subnets and then any associated network interfaces.

For outbound traffic, the process is reversed. Azure first evaluates network security group security rules for any associated network interfaces followed by any associated subnets.

For both the inbound and outbound evaluation process, Azure also checks how to apply the rules for intra-subnet traffic. Intra-subnet traffic refers to virtual machines in the same subnet.

Now you might have a genuine reason why you want to put something at the NIC level to either redirect your traffic more specifically or a sort or pseudo quarantine where you still need to access the network but you can't let something compromised interact with the okay parts of your subnet. But generally you'll be fine with using an nsg at the subnet level.

